00:01.740 --> 00:12.300
Okay, the tape is on. Would you give us some biographical data on how you grew
up and how you got interested in writing science fiction. Well, I grew up in

00:12.300 --> 00:24.740
Kansas. Both of my parents teach. At least my mother used to and then she became
a newspaper woman. So we, I grew up with words around the house, a lot. Oh, I

00:24.740 --> 00:33.740
was making up stories from, well, I guess I was four or five, the kind of thing
where mother reads you the bedtime story and puts you to bed and nobody feels

00:33.740 --> 00:45.120
like going to sleep yet. So since I was too young to read, I hadn't discovered
reading on the covers with flashlights yet, I made up stories until I was ready

00:45.120 --> 00:55.580
to go to sleep. And then I started writing them down when I learned to write.
And about junior high school, I discovered science fiction. Up to then, it was

00:55.580 --> 01:10.940
cowboys and horses, with a lot of girls, I think. I discovered science fiction
in junior high, and I don't know why it caught me the way it did. I kind of got

01:10.940 --> 01:23.100
away from it later and got strictly into mystery, and then came back to science
fiction when I was in college. and I've been hooked on science fiction mysteries

01:23.100 --> 01:27.680
ever since. You probably noticed that a lot of the combination of the two in my
work.

01:30.840 --> 01:42.160
Being a little Kansas girl did you ever read the Oz books? No, as a matter of
fact I think aside from The Wizard of Oz I think I'd only seen I knew there were

01:42.160 --> 01:49.480
a number of others because I had some friends that had others but I'd never read
them and I still haven't read them.

01:52.440 --> 02:02.080
The dedications to all five of the books that you have in print now are all to
Pat. He must have influenced you a great deal. Could you give some background

02:02.080 --> 02:19.920
into that influence and how he helped you get where you are? When we got
married, I was writing. We got married back in 66, and I think that Star Trek

02:19.920 --> 02:31.440
was either on the air, I think it was on the air at the time, and like a lot of
people I got really hooked on Star Trek and was writing episodes for it, and I

02:31.440 --> 02:41.880
guess at that time we were just going together. At any rate, when we got
married, I had stopped writing Star Trek and writing some stuff of my own and he

02:41.880 --> 02:49.900
got ignored somewhat because I was busy writing and he said as long as you are
going to be doing that, why don't you try sending it out? He bugged me, bugged

02:49.900 --> 03:01.640
me until I finally started sending things out and once I got sent sending stuff
out, of course I had lots of rejections. he was very good about letting me cry

03:01.640 --> 03:10.700
on his shoulder and also very candid about his opinion in on the various
stories, some which led to grand battles, but he usually turned out to be right.

03:12.580 --> 03:23.620
So he was very influential in getting me writing and in getting me sending out
and keeping me sending out. And then once the story started selling, and once I

03:23.620 --> 03:38.580
turned to novels, he was my critic and chief cheerleader. and I understand there
are a lot of spouses that writers don't like to consult with their spouses very

03:38.580 --> 03:48.100
much because they're either too critical or they're not critical enough. But Pat
is very objective and he's an excellent critic and he knows, he has a good feel

03:48.100 --> 03:58.300
for what is right and what's wrong with a story. And he has to hear everything I
read chapter by chapter and all the revisions so he's very patient and long

03:58.300 --> 04:11.660
-suffering and he puts up with being ignored evening after evening so that I can
write because I've got deadlines I have to meet. He understands that. He makes

04:11.660 --> 04:18.140
sure I don't kill myself. Well, he comes in and pulls the plug on the typewriter
at 2 or 3 in the morning if I'm starting to pull an all-nighter to make sure I

04:18.140 --> 04:29.820
get to sleep because I do have a job to get to the next morning. So he's very
important. He's, as I say, a chief critic and cheerleader. he's now also my

04:29.820 --> 04:41.360
business manager he handles the publicity he talks to the TV stations to get the
interviews on TV to get autograph sessions set up he handles plane tickets and

04:41.360 --> 04:53.020
hotel reservations and all the business ends he's an attorney so he's an expert
on copyright and he's starting to get seminars on copyright as a matter of fact

04:54.140 --> 05:04.420
and he handles all the taxes and all the business work So, it's kind of a
partnership. I do the writing and get the publishing done. And he does all the

05:04.420 --> 05:05.360
work that keeps it going.

05:08.560 --> 05:17.000
According to the bios in the backs of some of the books, it also says that Pat
introduced you to science fiction fandom and to science fiction conventions. Do

05:17.000 --> 05:25.900
you find these a great help to your writing? I've met a lot of writers at the
science fiction conventions. I've just been doing short stories. and it was

05:25.900 --> 05:35.020
meeting the writers that got me started writing the novels because they were the
ones who were saying, that's the only place you're going to make any money or

05:35.020 --> 05:42.580
make any kind of name for yourself. But short stories, you can't make any money
in short stories. And, of course, some of the writers have become some of my

05:42.580 --> 05:51.600
dearest friends now. I really like talking about writing. So I love meeting fans
who want to do nothing more than sit up all night and talk about science fiction

05:51.600 --> 06:03.520
and writing. and I really think that it helps because you meet people, and then
you're a face to them, not just a name, and they'll read something that is

06:03.520 --> 06:14.240
written by someone they know, and then they can recommend it to friends, and I
realize that only a very small percentage of the population is in fandom and

06:14.240 --> 06:25.640
attends a convention. If all the fans in the United States bought a book, it
would be a failure. You have to have a lot more than that. But still, I think it

06:25.640 --> 06:36.220
helps. And you get used to talking to people and get used to going on TV shows.
Pretty soon, I'm going to make some trips to the East Coast this year, and I

06:36.220 --> 06:44.820
hope soon to make some trips to the West Coast, which means I'll get autograph
sessions at bookstores out there, which will get my name spread a little wider.

06:46.260 --> 06:56.240
So aside from being a lot of fun, I think that as far as a writing career goes,
that going to the convention is very, it pays.

07:00.340 --> 07:11.700
You also work full-time, as I understand it. Would you describe what your real
-world job is and also how you schedule your writing and your job so you can get

07:11.700 --> 07:24.060
both done? well the job is a regular 9 to 5 job as it happens I'm chief
technologist in the department of radiology at the college of veterinary

07:24.060 --> 07:34.960
medicine I'm an x-ray technician for animals in what it amounts to I'm in charge
of educating the vet students that is I'm in charge of them when they're in the

07:34.960 --> 07:46.480
department itself which is sort of a laboratory situation for them and I think
It's a 9-to-5 job, and then I come home and write in the evening. I usually end

07:46.480 --> 07:58.240
up taking a notebook with notes on whatever the current work is to work with me,
and there's a hiatus now and then. And when that happens, I can sit down and jot

07:58.240 --> 08:09.160
notes. I can't actually get any writing done. I've got too much to do, and there
isn't enough of a long span of no work to get anything done. but a lot of times

08:09.160 --> 08:20.360
in the midst of purely physical activity or purely routine activity at work,
something I've been having a problem with, for instance, or an idea for a

08:20.360 --> 08:30.820
revision or an idea of something to do in the chapter ahead will come up, and I
can jot it down. I'm still working while I'm in the real world job because my

08:30.820 --> 08:39.860
subconscious is still grinding away of whatever the writing project is at home,
And then I come home when I write in the evening and I'll write through on

08:39.860 --> 08:52.680
weekends, too. How do your colleagues and students at work take to your writing?
What do they think about it? They're very tickled about it. I didn't know how

08:52.680 --> 09:04.700
administration and some of the doctors, the clinicians, would take to it because
science fiction in many quarters thought of as a very lowbrow kind of writing.

09:04.700 --> 09:14.940
writing, but I find that they're very pleased about it when the dean of the vet
school brings people to our hospital on a tour. He usually makes mention of the

09:14.940 --> 09:25.060
fact that I'm a public science fiction writer, and I've gotten a couple of
attaboy kind of letters from the president of the university. And we have, of

09:25.060 --> 09:35.080
course, journalism students at the university, and I'm usually good for for
about one appearance in the paper per semester, as one of the journalism

09:35.080 --> 09:48.740
students has to get his so many inches of copy in, and almost always one of them
will appear. I'm pretty well publicized around campus, and I don't find them

09:48.740 --> 10:00.020
looking down on me because I'm being published in fiction and science fiction
instead of in scientific journals, like most of them get published. So they take

10:00.020 --> 10:09.740
it very well and my boss is a real king. I usually turn in my convention
schedule to him at the beginning of summer. He fits his vacations in between my

10:09.740 --> 10:15.460
convention schedule. And he lets me off almost any weekend I want during the
year to go to conventions too.

10:19.840 --> 10:30.320
Our first exposure to you as a novelist was A Voice out of Rama. And that book
seemed to set the tone for some of your subsequent works with the various

10:30.320 --> 10:39.860
elements in it. As you mentioned previously, it's got a bit of a mystery,
although not quite as much as some of the other novels. How did you come to

10:39.860 --> 10:43.900
write this book? How long did the idea sit there percolating before it came out?

10:46.640 --> 10:56.620
I don't really know. I try to keep track of the process of creativity because it
fascinates me. Also, because as a writer I'm asked so many questions about where

10:56.620 --> 11:07.540
ideas come from and how they develop that I keep trying to find out. I had a
couple of writers who ganged up on me at some conventions convincing me that I

11:07.540 --> 11:08.960
really needed to write a novel.

11:11.740 --> 11:22.920
And I don't know, just these little bits and pieces just all came together. I
keep telling people that creativity is a little bit like recombinant DNA. all

11:22.920 --> 11:34.860
the little everything you read and see and hear breaks up into component parts
and proves around your subconscious until it reaches a critical mass that is

11:34.860 --> 11:43.740
also viable and then it rises to the surface and you start putting ideas around
it because the idea that comes up is just the grain in the middle you have to

11:43.740 --> 11:58.980
add all the rest of it around but I had tried to do some Sherlock Holmes
pastitions. And one of them was a reverse, where all the Holmes, Watson

11:58.980 --> 12:11.240
characters were females. And I had half invented a planet that had a matriarchy.
So that got me started thinking about how a matriarchy would work, and why it

12:11.240 --> 12:26.720
would develop. And so I found myself working back for causes like that, And all
of a sudden I had the society that I used then in Voice Out of Rama. And once I

12:26.720 --> 12:34.480
had the society, I just kind of sat down and thought, well, what kind of plot
elements, what kind of conflicts can arise out of this society that would

12:34.480 --> 12:44.300
probably not arise out of any other? And who is the one that's going to be most
affected by these? And so I came up with the plot that way, and I came up with

12:44.300 --> 12:53.580
my major character that way. After that, it was fun just building the planet and
trying to make it as realistic and as logical as I could.

12:58.200 --> 13:09.000
Then the doppelganger gamut came along, and it seemed to be quite a change of
pace since it was basically a police procedure science fiction novel. You seem

13:09.000 --> 13:18.120
to be very familiar with police procedure, with how partners have the
interaction, that sort of thing? Is this something from your background or did

13:18.120 --> 13:27.280
you have to research this? I haven't had any practical experience in it. I did
have a police officer come up to me at a science fiction convention once when

13:27.280 --> 13:37.280
I'd been reading a chapter of Doppelganger. And he asked me when I worked in law
enforcement. But I've been interested in law enforcement for a long time. I

13:37.280 --> 13:46.100
noticed that the mysteries I always liked to read were the ones in which the
police were the good guys. I was never particularly interested in the lone wolf

13:46.100 --> 14:02.720
private eye. I got listened to Dragnet on the radio and saw it on TV when I was
pretty small, and I think maybe that's my first brush with police work, and I

14:02.720 --> 14:13.160
was just very interested in it. Joseph Wambau is one of my favorite authors, and
I happened to know somebody, by the way, who gave him a copy of Doppelganger

14:13.160 --> 14:17.280
Gambit, and he told his friend that he really liked it a lot, which tickled me.

14:20.940 --> 14:35.240
Once I decided I wanted to write a mystery science fiction, I went ahead and did
more research, and I've kept into it, and of course that book itself and others

14:35.240 --> 14:48.200
have brought me into contact with more police officers, and they've passed on a
lot of material to me. And so, short of actually working in it myself, I have

14:48.200 --> 14:58.080
gotten very familiar with it. I suppose I keep reading about it, or writing
about it, because it was interesting and because I've done so much research on

14:58.080 --> 15:11.420
it that it's a shame not to use the material. The key to that book for me was
the characters, Jana Brill and Mama Maxwell. Were they based on people you'd

15:11.420 --> 15:12.660
known before, or what?

15:16.300 --> 15:27.240
No, they were based on nobody I know, except that I always pictured Mama Maxwell
as looking like Luke Ossett Jr., which I was very surprised, then, to get the

15:27.240 --> 15:35.960
cover proof and find that the cover artist, Michael Herring, had also pictured
him the same way and found a model that looked so much like the character that

15:35.960 --> 15:37.160
I'd pictured. It was wonderful.

15:40.820 --> 15:49.240
Somewhere in the beginning when I was putting the book together, which had
started as a novelette, and I knew it couldn't be a novelette because here I was

15:49.240 --> 16:04.440
15 pages into something and just barely starting it, I had decided I wanted to
use a Lady Cop. So for contrast, I gave her a male partner and I can't remember

16:04.440 --> 16:16.100
why I decided to make him black it was one of these things that just kind of
happened somebody later pointed out that I had my female character was the one

16:16.100 --> 16:23.520
that was working by the book and procedure and my male character was the one who
was working on intuition which is an interesting reverse on the way people

16:23.520 --> 16:32.440
generally think of males and females and that just sort of happened the
characters sort of balanced one another but a lot of the balance was unconscious

16:32.440 --> 16:41.560
on my part they were fun characters and I intend to work with them again. So we
will see them again. Oh, yes. As soon as I can think of something more for them

16:41.560 --> 16:50.580
to get into. One of the other things that I really noticed in the book that made
it that much more realistic was the slang. I'm particularly curious where the

16:50.580 --> 17:03.460
term Leos came from, a reference to the police officers. I would think I was
seeing something about law enforcement officers one time and I noticed that it

17:03.460 --> 17:15.160
made Leo, And I thought, that's great, because it gave rise in my mind to all
kinds of connotations, and I could see police officers enjoying being called

17:15.160 --> 17:27.100
Leos because of the lion, the fierce kind of association you get with it, and
therefore calling police stations lion den. And someone who's likely to be

17:27.100 --> 17:38.740
picked up by the police is lion meat. I had a pejorative I had the street people
calling them pussies when they weren't happy with them but my editor wouldn't

17:38.740 --> 17:46.940
let me keep the word in the book so I think it got changed to kitty a couple of
times in the book and I illuminated it where possible because I really didn't

17:46.940 --> 17:56.880
like watered down I really did want to use pussy because it seemed to me like
the normal way people would pick up and twist something when they wanted to make

17:56.880 --> 18:07.240
a derogatory term out of it I enjoy the slang. I enjoy trying to figure out
where slang comes from and where it's going to go. And you may have noticed in a

18:07.240 --> 18:18.020
number of the books that I've played on slang, there's quite a bit of it in
Deadly Silence. And I'm even having some alien slang in the current work I'm

18:18.020 --> 18:31.540
doing. Deadly Silence seemed, I took, to be in the same future history as the
doppelganger gambit. They all are, as a matter of fact, except monitor. That was

18:31.540 --> 18:41.680
in a different one. And there you went a little bit into the etymology of the
word cop. I didn't realize that's where it came from until I read it in that

18:41.680 --> 18:47.760
book. There are several possibilities.

18:50.680 --> 19:02.200
They usually teach a little bit of that in police history. When they're teaching
in police academies, One thought it meant constable on patrol, and sometimes it

19:02.200 --> 19:11.000
said, well, it comes from the copper buttons that they used to wear. And the
exact origin of the word isn't known. But it's interesting to me to stumble

19:11.000 --> 19:22.400
across the term conservator of peace way back in early England. And it seems to
me that an alien who was reading Earth's history and having come across the word

19:22.400 --> 19:29.440
cop, referring to police officers, and the earlier conservative of peace,
conservator of peace, might connect the two.

19:33.500 --> 19:42.440
I found it interesting that the duties of the cops, you did call them cops from
then on, from chapter 2 or whatever, for the rest of the book, because of the

19:42.440 --> 19:50.880
connotations of Leos. I found it interesting that their first priority was to
the victim, and then, lo and behold, later on, they have to defend the

19:50.880 --> 20:05.600
perpetrator. Where did you come up with these seemingly novel ideas? They kind
of grew out of the society of the Aragara because the primary objective of the

20:05.600 --> 20:11.000
police there was, of course, to restore peace, to be peace officers.

20:15.240 --> 20:28.840
and of course when anything happened that was distressful to the Aragara it was
painful to everybody around them. So the first duty then was to the victim to

20:28.840 --> 20:40.980
help them understand what had happened to them. I suppose it reflects a little
bit of a reaction to some of the things that I've seen in our own culture where

20:40.980 --> 20:50.320
the victim suffers a lot because everybody's so interested in catching the guy
who did it a lot of times they're not paying too much attention to the victim

20:50.320 --> 20:59.700
himself. Things are changing a little bit now with victims suing perpetrators

20:59.700 --> 21:01.140
and collecting

21:03.340 --> 21:16.580
and people who are convicted of crimes in some states have to make restitution
to victims. so I thought I would just kind of carry that into a society that was

21:16.580 --> 21:30.300
not was less interested in punishing than in simply stopping the problem,
whatever it was and since their system had no regular system for defense

21:30.300 --> 21:39.800
attorneys it seemed to me that it would naturally fall on the only people that
were involved in the criminal legal system which would be the ones who are also

21:39.800 --> 21:53.660
working for the prosecutor. Actually, ideally, even in our culture, in a sense,
the police should be working for the defendant because if they can remove any

21:53.660 --> 22:06.120
doubt that he's guilty, then when they take the case to court, why, it'll be a
much sounder case. But it often happens that expedience gets in the way and pick

22:06.120 --> 22:14.240
someone who's likely and find all the evidence against them instead of sifting
through all the evidence and then picking the only person who could possibly be

22:14.240 --> 22:15.380
the guilty party.

22:18.520 --> 22:30.380
Since you said that Doppelganger, Rama, and Deadly Silence are all in the same
future history, can you give us an idea of the chronological order, maybe the

22:30.380 --> 22:40.960
distance, the time difference between those three books? and do you plan to
write in this future history? I know you mentioned that you have a sidebar to

22:40.960 --> 22:51.440
Doppelganger Gambit. Do you plan to do a lot more writing in this future
history? I think I will. It offers a lot of opportunities. There are any number

22:51.440 --> 22:56.980
of planets available to set stories on. and

23:00.860 --> 23:19.600
it cover a long span of time Doppelganger is the earliest because it's set right
in the next century and then it's possible that voice out of Rama could come

23:19.600 --> 23:31.540
about at the same time as as Deadly Silence but probably not the ships that set
out to take shuttle boxes to the various colonies and put them in contact with

23:31.540 --> 23:46.460
the rest of the universe again set out about the time the shuttle box was
developed and got perfected so they had ships out running around and by the time

23:46.460 --> 23:59.600
one particular ship got to the planet, got to Mara why it may have been several
hundred years even after Deadly Silence. But Deadly Silence and Voice Out of

23:59.600 --> 24:13.820
Rama are very close to each other, within a century or two of each other. Deadly
Silence is five or six hundred years after A Voice Out of Rama. And, of course,

24:13.900 --> 24:31.900
the one I'm writing at the moment is within a century. of the doppelganger
gambit. It's a little difficult figuring real time and the fact that they had

24:31.900 --> 24:47.540
time dilation going on their ship. So they were actually 10 years away from
Earth when everything happened. So in actual real time, probably the book I'm

24:47.540 --> 24:50.740
writing now and the doppelganger gambit happen almost simultaneously.

24:56.740 --> 25:10.020
Your fourth novel, The Monitor of the Miners and the Shri is completely
different. And as you said, it's in a different future history. Will you do any

25:10.020 --> 25:20.980
writing in that future history? Or what was it? The Sodality? That was the the
governing organization. that's a future history that i was working on as a

25:20.980 --> 25:29.460
teenager and which started out as very peaceful and wonderful and tended to get
much more complex and much more violent the older i got the more i realized that

25:29.460 --> 25:38.420
people just didn't get along with each other all the time i have several short
stories that are said in that particular universe and i'll probably come back to

25:38.420 --> 25:49.460
it again it's an interesting one because it has a lot of different groups none
of which are human and offers possibilities for societies and interplays. And

25:49.460 --> 26:00.660
aliens, the future history I have set up, the one that most of the novels are
in, has a minimal of aliens the far we actually want to run across. One, which

26:00.660 --> 26:11.220
is spacing. And then, of course, there's the aliens that are on the planet on
which the colonists

26:11.220 --> 26:17.600
who are in trouble on the Invictus lands, the book I'm working on at the moment,
has some aliens on it. But there's a minimal of aliens, and if I want to deal

26:17.600 --> 26:28.700
with alien species, it's just really easy to go to that other future history
which has all kinds of aliens running around. I like to think of it as just

26:28.700 --> 26:39.340
being across, being on our same galaxy, it's just on the other side, way out of
contact with us, probably not where we're likely to run into it very soon. I'd

26:39.340 --> 26:49.660
like to ask you a question here, not so much as a science fiction writer, just
from all your experience up to now. What is your idea of aliens, as far as real

26:49.660 --> 26:59.840
life is concerned? We have the idea that there are a lot of them. Other people
have the idea that maybe life is abundant, but intelligence is not. Do you have

26:59.840 --> 27:04.940
any feelings about that one way or the other, predictions now.

27:09.740 --> 27:23.380
I just can't feel that we're the only intelligent species in the galaxy. In the
universe. With infinite possibilities and infinite worlds out there, possibly

27:23.380 --> 27:32.940
less of them habitable by our standards than we might like to think because you
have to have them within a continual life zone instead of these edges where they

27:32.940 --> 27:46.340
keep slipping in and out of a limestone. So maybe the possibilities for really
intelligent life are fewer, but I think they're out there somewhere, and I would

27:46.340 --> 28:00.300
really love to meet one. This book strikes me as coming closest to a so-called
hard science fiction book, and you evidently put in a lot of work on the biology

28:00.300 --> 28:12.160
and the evolutionary facts of the Sri. Is this something that you've been
thinking about since you were a teenager? Or how did that evolve? I think it's

28:12.160 --> 28:13.040
kind of evolved.

28:15.620 --> 28:26.380
Because of my husband's interest in psychology and law, I started out and my
interest was mostly in really hard science fiction. I was a die-hard analog

28:26.380 --> 28:39.120
reader. and the first story ever sold was to analog and it was an analog kind of
story I haven't sold a story to analog since almost everything I've written

28:39.120 --> 28:48.900
since has come out in well the majority of it's come out fantasy and science
fiction I've had one in Galileo and a couple in his magazine before it folded

28:50.320 --> 28:59.180
but I got more and more interested in people and realizing that hardware wasn't
the thing that it was people and that people were interesting and what made them

28:59.180 --> 29:11.980
tick. And so the more I started researching that, the more I got interested in
what makes societies click. And then when I started making up aliens and I

29:11.980 --> 29:22.020
started reading a lot of anthropology to figure out really how societies go
together, the more I read, the more I researched, the more fascinated I got. I

29:22.020 --> 29:32.300
put together a background book before I ever start. the novel itself. It's an
amount of work that I know some people find exhausting.

29:33.060 --> 29:43.800
They couldn't do it and still write. They have any energy left to write the
book. But I enjoy it. I'm very systematic. I start out with a lot of visual

29:43.800 --> 29:54.900
images in my head. And with vague visual images, you have to have them developed
to a very clear, you have to develop a very clear image and you have to find the

29:54.900 --> 30:04.600
words for them and get them translated into actual words out of pictures before
you can get them down on paper so i do a background book and i do maps of the

30:04.600 --> 30:18.320
planet and i do drawings of the flora and fauna and biographies of the people
and the more i read and read on climatology and planetology the more complex

30:18.320 --> 30:28.680
backgrounds get now it takes me It takes me about the same amount of time to put
a background together, but it gets much more complicated. Now the finished

30:28.680 --> 30:38.140
background is almost as thick as the final manuscript on the book. I keep
finding out how complex societies and ecologies are. There's no way, of course,

30:38.140 --> 30:52.900
I can really create one in detail. But I keep working at making them as logical
and as realistic as I can. I keep discovering how much people are influenced by

30:52.900 --> 31:05.860
their cultures in very unconscious ways. And I strive to make an alien that is
genuinely alien, but of course not so much that a human won't be interested in

31:05.860 --> 31:20.020
reading about them. But so that they will react in very alien ways, I work out
the culture down to jokes they think are funny and what the musical instruments

31:20.020 --> 31:34.300
are and what toys their kids play with and maybe even what their plumbing looks
like. So I have the whole society created in such detail in my own mind that the

31:34.300 --> 31:47.000
characters' actions will be influenced by their environment. And a lot of times
I find conflicts in the story then growing out of that society, so they don't

31:47.000 --> 31:56.920
just sound like a plot that's been picked up and translated from mainstream
Earth. There are things that happened then that could only have happened on that

31:56.920 --> 32:01.520
particular planet because of their particular attitudes, because of their
particular environment and culture.

